of intact and dysmorphic cells","Predominantly intact red blood cells","Predominantly ghost cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn glomerular haematuria, \u003Cstrong\u003Egreater than 80% dysmorphic red blood cells\u003C/strong\u003E are seen on phase contrast microscopy. This occurs because red blood cells become damaged as they squeeze through the glomerular basement membrane.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELess than 20% dysmorphic red blood cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This pattern suggests non-glomerular bleeding where cells remain intact\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEqual mixture of intact and dysmorphic cells\u003C/strong\u003E - The pattern is usually predominantly one type rather than mixed\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPredominantly intact red blood cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Intact cells indicate non-glomerular bleeding\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPredominantly ghost cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Ghost cells are not typically seen in fresh specimens\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis microscopic assessment is only reliable in microscopic haematuria. With macroscopic bleeding, the high volume of blood makes morphological assessment unreliable.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Glomerular haematuria shows \u003E80% dysmorphic red blood cells due to mechanical damage during passage through the glomerular basement membrane","Non-glomerular haematuria shows predominantly intact red blood cells as they do not pass through the glomerular filter","Phase contrast microscopy is only reliable for examining microscopic haematuria, not macroscopic bleeding"],"references":["Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (